Author: alexcartagenamex#4215
Content:
I feel there is a bit of a misunderstanding here. IMHO. RAwDao and it‚Äôs discord is not much about building a community of photographers and having the community happen inside of it. If we try to do this, we will slowly create a possibility a bit of resentment as to why they are not being collected, because why would they be here if not to be seen and bought?! This happens in many discord where all it becomes is people dumping images to see if they get picked. RAwDao will be scouting for those photographers anyway. The New Community photography collection will have that role, to scout for new talent from inside the NFT space. So do we need a community of photographers? If we do, which would be great let‚Äôs help them with building a community about sharing ideas. Just be mindful about this. 

RAwDao is about building a community around the power of a collection. We are sending signals that we are a group of sophisticated thinkers that, like FP, have a very very very clear vision of the power of photography. The taste and efficacy of our curation is what will create the community! If we build that, all eyes will be on us. If we are sloppy, we will just attract people looking for ‚Äúopportunities‚Äù to dump their stuff on our collection. If we build a really strong collection, the best talent will rally behind us and help us fulfill our mission of being the best photography collection in the world. Again, the collection is the community. We have a perfect collection like FP, everyone will come to us. 

What do you think?

Author: alexcartagenamex#4215
Content: So we need to create the 2 collections. Here are the ideas @gallegosfer and myself have shared with the team before:

Author: alexcartagenamex#4215
Content:
**A PROPOSAL FOR RAW DAO‚Äôs 
CURATORIAL VISION**


INTRODUCTION

In the newly born NFT artworld, photography has been gaining popularity since the success of Justin Aversano‚Äôs Twin Flames in the early 2021. Since then, a wave of photographers have taken over the space with relative success taking advantage of a crescent interest in collectors for high quality photographic work. But the space lacks a history of the art and clear markers of what is and has been considered valuable in photography historically, creating uncertainty in photography as a long term investment. Until now, photography has served principally 2 purposes, one is as a collectible easy to flip because of its current popularity, the other as a collectible that the collector simply ‚Äúlikes‚Äù for personal visual/emotional reasons. The true historical and social value of a photo-work has not been taken into account in a serious way yet in a broad sense and to make a healthy environment of creation and collection of photography as an art, a signal has to be made to cut through the current noise and to help point to quality work being produced inside the NFT world as well as in the traditional artworld.

The RAW DAO‚Äôs curatorial mission in the NFT space is to create a strong signal of what‚Äôs considered a quality photographic work of the highest standards in a historical context while also acknowledging the new photographic movement emerging from within the space from the interaction of creators and collectors. For this purpose, the RAW DAO‚Äôs vault will hold two collections, The Legacy Collection and The New Community Photography Collection:

Author: alexcartagenamex#4215
Content:
**The Legacy Collection**:
Will be conformed of collected works by established artists in the traditional artworld with the objective of creating a record of high quality and historically valuable art photography that can help as a guide for the community of what‚Äôs considered important photography as art, to this purpose, the curatorial committee will take into account established artists that are already onboarded in the NFT world and also artists that can be considered for onboarding with the purpose of adding work from them to the collection.

**The New Community Photography Collection**:
Will be formed of photographic work that is considered important by the community itself as a way to give voice to the values of this evolving community that we call the NFT world. The community curatorial committee will take into account work that‚Äôs already in important collections of the NFT artworld and work that has been important for the short history of photography in the NFT space without discrimination of style, concept or formal approach . This collection will also be on the lookout for new work being produced and valued in the NFT world by creators and collectors alike and will have the objective of creating a record of the evolution of photography in this space, a collection that can become a marker for new cultural aesthetic values.


CONCLUSION.

These two collections will help gather the best photographic work being created as NFTs, both from established artists from the traditional artworld in an effort of honoring the history of the photographic art and from new artists being valued by the community for sharing a vision with it towards different themes through their photographic art as a way to support and push forward new and different ways of understanding photography as an art and as a form of social communication.

Author: mdr#8647
Content:
Can find myself fully in the BHAG !! For the most part I agree with the whole plan, the intentions and goals. Also the current problems signalled in the NFT photo space are real and need to be addressed in order for photo NFT to have a future in the long run and in order to establish connection with the traditional photo world. 

What I am missing a bit though is how RAWdao acquires liquidity in the future. With the funds coming out of the PartyBid liquidity will be guaranteed for quite some time, but not forever.

How will new funds be raised for the DAO? There will be some value derived from the RAW tokens through appreciation. There will be value in the NFTs in the DAOs vault, but will RAWdao trade them? And if so, how will be decided what and when they are to be traded? There is a risk RAWdao will be flipping NFT in the same way as currently is the speculative practice, which might undo part of RAWs purpose. 

Already with the PartyBid strategy to establish liquidity RAW is walking a thin line in this respect - though I must add it is conceptually fantastic to fracture this historic work to a thousand owners in a way returning the work in the ownership of the community. Don‚Äôt know if that is intentional though, but this concept of shared ownership of important work might also be a strategy for the future - it fits web3 philosophy. Let‚Äôs fracture Andreas Gurski‚Äôs ‚Äú*Rhein II*‚Äù ‚ö° 

So maybe it is smart to think about how to raise liquidity by maybe also initiating projects that will raise funds. For now, for this plan, this doesn‚Äôt need to be concrete, but it might be good to put in the Strategic Plan some kind of intention to explore this.

Author: lucaspon#3865
Content:
borrowing from the experience in fingerprints, there's a few ways to raise liquidity available for the DAO:
1- primary token sales: we still have a huge amount of tokens in treasury which we can sell to raise funds;
2- capital raises: for instance, from venture capital funds interested in investing in web3.0
3- revenue generating projects: where we can, for example, create new nft projects in partnership with artists and retain a portion of the proceeds from the initial sales and secondary royaltee fees
4- other initiatives we don't anticipate, such as artistic events and exhibitions where we can perhaps earn from ticket sales or a number of things we haven't thought about.

Author: lucaspon#3865
Content: also we can earn from providing liquidity to our own token in decentralized exchanges

Author: lucaspon#3865
Content: and from staking stationary funds

Author: lucaspon#3865
Content: but these are mostly secondary sources.

Author: lucaspon#3865
Content: all in all there's plenty of work to do before the next liquidity round

Author: glory#5406
Content:
IMO - photography is such a broad space with a long history, that we'd be doing ourselves a disservice if we restricted the curation effort to only those already minted, or only those not minted. It should be Web3 agnostic.

We have the opportunity to do both:
A) Identify historically important traditional photographers who may not even know what an NFT is, and help them onboard their work into a Web3 modality
B) Identify influential photographers who may have already dabbled in NFTs, and help them refine their Web3 strategy and expand their work to a wider audience.

Both of these can fit in the confines of a "legacy" collection. I think constricting the parameters to either "already minted" or "never minted" would be counterproductive.

Author: hddamico#7928
Content:
@everyone would like your feedback on this

1) Curated Collection Committee 
Testing period: 4 weeks, after that voting to decide new members
- Number of Members: 3 @Founding Artists + 7 collectors (initial formation)
- Budget: 120 ETH (e.g.15% of our treasury)
Committee role / responsibilities: 
(i) get nominations from members/community in a dedicated channel, on a weekly basis
(ii) decide to collect or not 
(iii) decide acquisition strategy, size, timing and etc.
(iv) provide feedback (Y / N) to the community and why 
(v) try to come with a standard short memo to compare one collection / artist with others / previous discussed cases
(vi) interact with marketing team / external relation to announce the acquisition after it is executed. 

Curated Artists will gain a special role in our discord after we acquire. 

2) Community Collection
To come in 4 weeks, we should wait to get a better sense of interactions with new members 
Build mechanics together with new members

Author: DT | Luiz#4149
Content:
Ok I have a few thoughts, since it looks like the discussion is straying away from the main point.

**At this initial stage, the only chance RAW has to make an impact on the world, engage membership, grow its token value and eventually be in a position to raise more funds is to collect work that will go up in value**

That doesn‚Äôt mean we collect ANY work that goes up in value. That doesn‚Äôt mean we have no curatorial perspective. But that does mean some aspirations like quotas, collecting outside of platforms or chains that are where the serious collectors collect, supporting friends, have to be contained. 

**Our biggest risk is irrelevance**

I liked the initial proposal by @hddamico because it skews in favor of collectors. We have plenty of photographers in the space, and the simple fact we exist with such a rich treasury will be beneficial to them. 

But the deal for collector is still unclear. It‚Äôs far from obvious that photography is a market that they should be spending their time and money. It‚Äôs part of our mission to show them the way.

If we hold ourselves too early to utopian ideas of supporting far and wide we don‚Äôt make an impact. 

My suggestions would be to make a few concentrated bets on the beginning, **fast**, on photographers that have quality and are already relatively validated by the current market. Then, we can start to think a bit more outside the box and spread our bets, eventually getting to a point where we‚Äôre able to deploy capital we don‚Äôt expect a short term return.

If we try to do everything from day one we increase our chances of failing. That would really be a shame.

Author: lightchronicler#4067
Content:
It doesn't have to be either or. There is a balance to be found.
It's also not about utopian ideas per se. Certainly quality of the collected work should always come first over any consideration of equal representation across gender/race/geographical area etc. Having said that, there is plenty of quality available across all those categories.
Also we are, to an extend, operating in a self fulfilling mechanism. That is to say what we collect will increase in value simply because WE are collecting it. As such we can be a leader instead of following  what is already deemed established.

Author: b_themouth#0088
Content: Taking in consideration the new information that arise from the great work from @mmiliszkiewicz , there are some addresses that can override any community vote if they want to. I want to propose that on the near future we can try to use quadratic vote or logarithmic vote power. Is that something that the DAO want? I think as we are not a VC company does make a lot of sense to have such discrepancies on voting power and this types of voting will make these discrepancies less noticeable going forward

Author: mdr#8647
Content: What is always an option is that members with less individual voting power can pool their votes together on certain subjects. But this issue has been mentioned a few times earlier and we have to think about this. The other dangers are of course voter fatigue and that the voting process gets overwhelmingly complex.

Author: zs#3807
Content: I mentioned it in #üé®‚îÇcuration , but nowhere is it actually stated that votes are weighted by ownership for the community curation

Author: b_themouth#0088
Content: I'm in other DAOs that use different system of voting. Quadratic voting is just applying a function on the number of tokens where the voting power is not linear with the increasing of the amount. Doesn't increase complexity imo but don't know if we have the tools for that yet

Author: mdr#8647
Content: Sounds interesting- is there an app for that?

Author: b_themouth#0088
Content: I know DAO tools from Aragon and other system can use it, not sure about snapshot though

Author: mdr#8647
Content: Have also wrote something about it there.

Author: b_themouth#0088

Author: tatiana#6176
Content: This is not exactly related to tech audit but I learned today that Diamond DAO (https://www.diamonddao.xyz/) is working on building internal tools for DAOs (a dashboard if you will) that measure engagement, voting frequency, demographics, diversity, etc., as well as compensation. V1 will be ready in a few weeks, something to look forward to! I get that there is a need to move fast in the beginning to lay the groundwork BUT it is also important to have a general understanding of involvement across the board: for example, if only 1% of members vote on proposals then community activation needs to be a part of the core effort (more notifications, twitter posts, longer voting periods, etc.)

Content:
The point that sticks in my mind which goes against read-only is that we might start to get an influx of active NFT traders who are looking for alpha and just front run purchases on collections by any photographers being repeatedly discussed in RAW threads - the gallery of onlookers might not be as purely motivated as we may think - but again, just experiencing the amount of degens in every other NFT discord group - its very obvious people will go to any lengths to just get alpha so they can make a quick buck. With degens in read-only subs, we might see some sudden spikes in collection sales based on speculation -  before RAW have even made any decisions - causing us to reconsider whats said in here.

Also, privacy of DAO members - to be able to express freely amongst fully aligned and paying members feels like a safe space - being watched by 'read-only' members will make me uncomfortable personally

Author: Zak_Krevitt#7060
Content:
100000% this is where my head is at as well ^^^ 

It's like when Nickelodeon moved their offices to universal studios and put in glass walls so the public could just gawk at them all day. It was awful. Employees lost motivation and felt scared and nothing was private. It makes everyone watch their words and actions a lot more and less progress is made. 

Also, you make a great point about front running, it seems like that would be the primary reason for wanting to see what we were doing. 
I don't think we're in a place fincacially yet where we really need to be giving out 'free trials', especially if it means loss of privacy and loss of buying power to inflated pricing.

*"yeah this is definitely an important question. thanks for asking.

we are still ironing it out, and working with customers (like you) to do it.

the main issue we‚Äôve heard with typical saas pricing is that it is unfair to daos who have a more fluid structure. per person per month just doesnt work.

Author: Seth üî≤ ¬≤#8330
Content:
Regarding governance, we must have a serious discussion on the tradeoffs we‚Äôre willing to make. 

First, regarding centralized decision making authority. Less decision makers means faster decisions, but also carries risks inherent to all centralization. Additionally certain decisions are too urgent to be put to community wide votes, and different types of voting mechanisms can and should be used for different decisions that need to be made. 

Second, regarding the form of centralization. Do we want a committee? Do we want delegates? If the answer is no to both, then we need to think of ways to create an engaged voting body. A pool of RAW could be set aside just for this purpose. Voters could be positively incentivized with raw (ie if you vote you get raw or if you vote several times in a row you get raw). Alternatively they could be negatively incentivized (less voting or manipulation of voting process results in slashing their share of that RAW pool).

Third, salaries. If we do end up having individuals dedicated to governance, what should they be paid? Should they be paid at all? That‚Äôs another discussion in and of itself.

Fourth, there are creative options beyond a centralized core team/delegates or incentives for all when it comes to voting. There could be several individuals whose responsibility is to herd/shepherd voters, like a ‚Äúwhip‚Äù in the US Congress. Again the same discussion around salary would emerge.
